      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, absolutely, underground life can be a major culprit! Mycorrhizal fungi, which are beneficial partners to roots, can sometimes be disrupted, impacting nutrient absorption. However, you must also consider root pests like nematodes, which are tiny, unseen threats that can severely damage roots. If the roots are being attacked or are struggling due to poor biology, they simply cannot function well enough to draw up nutrients, leading to those yellowing leaves. A small, targeted biological spray might help if you suspect fungal issues, but nematodes require specific treatments.",
